Loading up the Supermicro with Proxmox Backup Server (PBS) is a brilliant architectural decision. PBS isn't just a standard backup target; it uses enterprise-grade deduplication and incremental chunk-based backups. By running PBS on that 12-drive Supermicro chassis, you can back up your entire virtualization fleet from the Dell R710 with near-zero overhead, saving a massive amount of storage space.

Using your stack of old 2.5" laptop drives to populate the 24-bay Dell Compellent SC220 is a classic, high-efficiency system administration move. While they aren't enterprise-grade SAS drives, they are perfect for a low-stakes test environment. It lets you test configuration limits, map storage protocols, and practice disaster recovery without spending a single dollar.

Below is the complete blueprint to add to your repository as `STORAGE_DISASTER_LAB.md`. It outlines how to wire your laptop drives into the Compellent shelf, pass them to Proxmox, and orchestrate automated backups via the Supermicro PBS node.

