# 💾 Blueprint: Enterprise Storage Protocol & Disaster Recovery Lab

This guide maps out the deployment of an enterprise-grade storage network using a dedicated high-density disk shelf populated with salvaged 2.5" laptop drives, linked to a primary compute node and an independent Proxmox Backup Server (PBS) deduplication target.

```
 [ Primary Compute Host ] ------------ (NFS / iSCSI Network Link) ------------ [ High-Density Storage Shelf ]
     (Dell R710 Proxmox)                                                          (Compellent SC220 Array)
             |                                                                      (2.5" Salvaged Disks)
             | (Automated Deduplicated Backup Stream)
             v
 [ Backup Infrastructure Target ]
   (Supermicro 2U Node Running PBS)
   (12x 4TB IronWolf CMR Drives)

```

## 🔌 1. Tier 1: Hardware Interconnect & Disk Shelf Provisioning

Connecting an enterprise disk shelf to a host machine requires proper SAS controller topology.

### Step A: The HBA Controller Interface

1. To pass the individual salvaged laptop drives directly from the Dell Compellent SC220 to your operating system without hardware RAID interference, the host controller must be flashed to **IT Mode (Initiator Target)**.
2. Use an external Host Bus Adapter (HBA) card (such as an LSI 9207-8e or equivalent) installed in your compute machine.
3. Connect the HBA to the Compellent SC220 EM01 controllers using an SFF-8088 SAS cable.

### Step B: The Salvaged 2.5" Laptop Drive Array

1. Mount your salvaged laptop drives into the Compellent caddies and slide them into the 24-bay faceplate.
2. Because these are standard consumer 2.5" SATA drives being plugged into an enterprise SAS backplane, ensure your interposers or caddies pass the single-channel SATA signals through cleanly to the controller.
3. Boot up the chassis. The backplane will automatically negotiate downstream link speeds (typically 3Gbps or 6Gbps depending on the legacy drive controller age).

